Now confirmed as more than 66M from 30th October data: 66.1M. This should resolve as per earlier rationales.
Due to lifter travel restrictions, and an influx of post=pandemic travel we will an uptick in those traveling which will affect the number of screenings done.

According to the TSA website, there is around an average of 2 million travelers that are screened per day. Since there are 31 days in October there should be around 64 million, but due to the fluctuation being mostly over 2 million each day, it should add up to between 66 million and 74 million travelers being screened in October. Since the average would be below 66 million, there is a small chance that it may be between 58 million and 66 million.
There is an average of 2 million people screened daily and with that number there should be between 66 and 74 million people screened every month with room for fluctuation.
There are over 2 million people daily screened. This will put the average screening in a month between 66-74 million.

The TSA should screen between 66 and 74 million in October 2022. The current estimate is near 67 million but by end of October, I believe it would be near 69 million with the steady increase in the number of TSA screens. Therefore, I am certain that is will be higher than 66 million but less than 74 million.

I presume the WHO will declare the end to the pandemic (not too confident but I think it's likely within say 5 months. If it's soon, this could boost public morale in traveling and push it closer to pre-pandemic levels and possibly push it into the latter bins.

There is approximately two million people screened by TSA per day on average. There are 31 days in October. This would mean that on average 62,000 people would get screened in the month of October is the baseline. Considering that there are no major holidays in October that people would travel for, and that not many people take vacations in October, as those are reserved for the summer months, there is likely very little fluctuation from the baseline. In addition, in most places, October is a very reasonable time of year weather wise. In the the weather is cooling down everywhere but it is not too hot and not too cold. Therefore, there is a likelihood of less travel for that reason too. Rates of travel have gone up significantly in the past year because people are feeling more comfortable with Covid-19 and they became impatient sitting in their home. That leads me to put 86% in the 58 million to 66 million category.

There were 67,821,427 travellers between July 31st and August 30th, which is just above the 66 million cutoff for bin 4. I struggle to see October having more passengers than August, which makes bin 4 look very unlikely. I'm heavily readjusting towards bin 3 and a bit of bin 2 as a result.

@tabhuth These 37,000 people only account for a small fraction of the entire labor force and I assume a bigger bet yet still relatively small fraction of the TSA lines (assumption). My question would be how correlated are the number of full-time employees and number of persons traveling through TSA. I'm not adept at figuring this correlation out. My guess is that even though less full-time employees could mean more layoffs and thus more travel through TSA, the opposite could be argued in that the more there are full-time employees, the more money there is in the economy for people to spend on travel and vacation.

I do see realistic scenarios where the 66M+ bins are achievable, but I've since adopted a bias toward lower bins consistent with a new mental model.

Current levels are at around 88% of 2019 (comparing pre-pandemic). While there is pent-up demand for holiday season travel I think there will also be further disruptions and cancellations due to staff shortages as a consequence of pandemic issues such as staff lay-offs, directly through illnesses and even due to re-hiring delays. Seasonal weather issues may also start to cause disruption as a consequence of climate change.

In 2021 there were more than 57 million travelers, and in 2019 there were more than 72 million travelers. The number of travelers this year seems to have been higher than the corresponding number for 2021, but fewer than for 2019. I don't see a reason why the number of travelers in October for this year should exceed the corresponding number for 2019 (more than 74 million). However, I see such an event as more likely than the number of travelers for October of this year to be significantly less than the corresponding number for 2021 (less than 50 million).

In 2015 (a bit dated) there were about 900mm enplanements at US commercial airports. 900mm/12= 54mm per month. Spring and summer are the highest sustained travel volumes of the year. Since October is in the fall we'll assume a discount, but not under 50mm. Most likely a slight increase to perhaps 92-95% = 66.4-69.3M with some caution on levels dropping. Need to check what factors affect travel in October in particular to refine this one. 72m in 2019 followed by 26m and 57m the following two Octobers. Since about mid-march we are above 90% of pre-COVID travel. I'd place the odds at >2/3 that that ratio increases by October, rather than decreases.

The trend at the moment is returning to pre-pandemic levels, but there is still the possibility of a new variant/resurgence in the fall which could temporarily reverse the trend, as well as cost of living increases which may dent travel plans (business & pleasure). As a result, I'm initially leaning more towards bin 3.
